The Large Hadron Collider works by using electromagnetic fields to accelerate particles along a chosen direction. These particles strike a target particle, and their interaction results in the generation of several new particles. These particles can decay in a very short amount of time, turning into a "jet" of particles and energy. Our data is on 100000 of these jets. For each jet we have 14 pieces of data, each on a different variable of the jet. The Higgs Boson is one of these quickly-decaying particles, and the attempt to identify one in nature consists of interpreting the data of its decay jet.

imshow(table)
Above is a table of the different variables of each jet for which we have data.
The variable Pt is the momentum transverse to the direction of travel of the initial particle.
The variable eta represents the pseudo-rapidity - a spatial variable calculated using the polar angle - the angle of the jet relative to the path of travel of the initial particle.
Phi represents the azimuthal angle - the angle between the jet and the x-axis, where the x-axis is defined as the horizontal axis of the plane orthogonal to the path of travel of the initial particle.
The mass in this experiment is the sum of the invariant masses of all of the particles in our beam.
The variables ee2(listed as Eew in the chart) and ee3 are the two-point and three-point Energy Correction Function Ratios. The parameter beta in their formulas is a dimensionless parameter used to give weight to the angular separation between different particles in a jet. D2 is calculated as the ratio between ee3 and ee2, which can be used to identify the two-body structure of a jet.
The meaning box for Angularity was left blank, as angularity serves as a description of the variable as well as a name. Angularities are a class of jet shapes, and the angularity quantity is a classification of the jet within this class. A generalized formula for angularity is given, in this experiment the parameter alpha in the formula is two.
The variables t1, t2, and t3 are the 1, 2, and 3 subjettiness of the jet. They are a measurement of how well a jet can be described as being composed of 1, 2 or 3 subjets. t32 and t21 are ratios between t3 and t2 and between t2 and t1 respectively.
Decays in this experiment are reconstructed using the anti-kt R = 1.0 algorith. Using this algorithm every jet is given a value for the dimensionless parameter R. KtDeltaR is the difference in R values between two different subjets within one large R jet.

Making histograms of each row of our data, we can see that all of them except the azimuthal angle have distributions that can be worked with. Below we'll first normalize our histograms, then we'll try to fit normal and lognormal plots to our distributions.
